        "intro": "If your parent struggles to pay heating bills or faces a utility shut-off, Alaska's LIHEAP program provides direct assistance with fuel costs, electric bills, and emergency heating needs. The program helps with regular heating bills, crisis situations (like shut-off notices or less than 5 gallons of heating fuel), and weatherization services.\n\nYour parent qualifies if their household income is at or below 150% of the Federal Poverty Level — that's $2,443/month for a single person or $3,303/month for a couple in 2026. However, they must have at least $200 in out-of-pocket heating costs per year to be eligible. Because Alaska has multiple providers (state offices, tribal organizations), the application process and benefit amounts vary significantly depending on where your parent lives and their tribal status.",
