        "faqs": [
          {
            "question": "Can I use a family member as the respite provider?",
            "answer": "Yes, but the respite provider must be at least 18 years old and cannot live in the same home as your parent. They also cannot be you — the primary caregiver."
          },
          {
            "question": "What if I'm already getting respite help through another program?",
            "answer": "You cannot receive respite services through any other program while participating in Alabama Lifespan Respite. You must choose one program or the other."
          },
          {
            "question": "How much will I be reimbursed for respite care?",
            "answer": "The program doesn't disclose specific reimbursement amounts. You'll learn the details if approved, and reimbursement is based on submitted timesheets showing actual hours of respite care provided."
          },
          {
            "question": "What counts as a chronic illness or disability for this program?",
            "answer": "Any condition requiring around-the-clock care, documented by a healthcare professional. This includes physical disabilities, chronic illnesses, dementia, and other conditions — the program serves care recipients of any age with any qualifying condition."
          },
          {
            "question": "Can I care for more than one family member through this program?",
            "answer": "No, only one caregiver per household is eligible to apply, and only one care recipient per household may be listed on the application."
          },
          {
            "question": "How often can I use respite services once approved?",
            "answer": "The program doesn't specify limits on frequency, but you must submit timesheets documenting actual respite hours provided. Reimbursement depends on available funding and your approved allocation."
          }
        ],
