        "intro": "If your parent is 65+, blind, or disabled and living on a very low income, California's State Supplementary Payment (SSP) automatically adds up to $239.94/month on top of federal SSI benefits. Because SSP is tied directly to SSI eligibility, your parent gets both programs with one application — the combined benefit reaches $1,233.94/month for individuals and $2,098.83/month for couples in 2026.\n\nThis extra cash helps bridge the gap between federal benefits and California's higher cost of living. Your parent must have less than $2,000 in countable assets ($3,000 for couples) and meet strict income limits. The benefit amount decreases dollar-for-dollar with other income like pensions or Social Security retirement benefits.\n\nSSP is administered by the Social Security Administration, not California, so you'll work with the same office that handles SSI. If your parent already receives SSI, they're likely already getting SSP — check their benefit statement to confirm.",
