        "intro": "If your parent is 60 or older and struggling to make ends meet on a fixed income, Colorado's Old Age Pension (OAP) provides monthly cash payments to help cover basic living expenses. Your parent could receive up to $952 per month, though the exact amount varies by county and is reduced dollar-for-dollar by other income sources.\n\nBecause OAP requires recipients to apply for all other benefits first — including Social Security, SSI, and any pensions — this program typically serves as a safety net for those who don't qualify for or receive minimal benefits from federal programs. The program comes with strict income and asset limits: your parent must have less than $2,000 in countable resources ($3,000 for couples) and monthly income below the benefit maximum.",
