        "id": "florida-snap-food-assistance",
        "name": "SNAP Food Assistance",
        "shortName": "SNAP Food Assistance",
        "tagline": "Up to $300+ monthly toward groceries for seniors 60+ on fixed incomes.",
        "programType": "benefit",
        "complexity": "deep",
        "geographicScope": {
          "type": "federal",
          "stateVariation": true
        },
        "intro": "If your parent is 60+ and struggling with grocery costs, SNAP can provide monthly benefits on an EBT card to help cover food expenses. Because seniors get special eligibility rules in Florida, your parent only needs to meet the net income limit (not the gross income limit that applies to younger adults) and can have up to $4,500 in countable assets versus $3,000 for other households.\n\nBenefits are calculated as the maximum monthly allotment for your household size minus 30% of your net income. For example, a 2-person household might receive around $415/month. The EBT card works like a debit card at grocery stores for fruits, vegetables, meat, dairy, and grains — but not alcohol, tobacco, or prepared foods.\n\nAbout half of eligible seniors don't apply for SNAP, often because they don't realize they qualify. Medical expenses can lower your calculated net income, potentially making your parent eligible even if their income seems too high.",
