        "faqs": [
          {
            "question": "Can my parent keep their house if they qualify for KanCare Medicaid?",
            "answer": "Yes, if the home equity is under $713,000 and your parent intends to return home, or if a spouse or disabled child lives there. For nursing home residents, the home is protected if there's intent to return or certain family members live there."
          },
          {
            "question": "What if my parent's income is just over the limit?",
            "answer": "Kansas has a 'Medically Needy' program where your parent can 'spend down' excess income by paying medical bills. Once they've paid enough medical expenses, they can qualify for coverage."
          },
          {
            "question": "My parent gave money to grandchildren last year. Will this affect eligibility?",
            "answer": "Possibly. Kansas looks back 5 years at all asset transfers. Gifts or below-market sales can create penalty periods that delay Medicaid coverage. You should disclose all transfers when applying."
          },
          {
            "question": "What's the difference between nursing home coverage and home-based services?",
            "answer": "Both require the same level of care need (Nursing Facility Level of Care), but nursing home coverage is generally available immediately if eligible. Home-based services (HCBS waivers) have limited slots and waitlists, but allow your parent to stay home."
          },
          {
            "question": "My parent has Medicare. Do they still need KanCare Medicaid?",
            "answer": "If your parent qualifies for both, KanCare works with Medicare to cover what Medicare doesn't — like long-term care, some prescriptions, and services Medicare limits. Your parent must use Medicare first, then KanCare covers additional costs."
          },
          {
            "question": "How does this work if my parents are married?",
            "answer": "Special spousal impoverishment rules protect the community spouse (the one not needing care). The healthy spouse can keep more assets (around $154,140 in 2026) and income, so they're not left destitute while the other spouse gets Medicaid."
          }
        ],
