        "faqs": [
          {
            "question": "What if my parent's income is too high for Medicaid but they can't afford private insurance?",
            "answer": "PACE has private pay options for people who don't qualify for Medicaid. About 10% of PACE participants pay privately. Contact your local PACE provider for current premium rates."
          },
          {
            "question": "Can my parent keep their current doctors?",
            "answer": "No. PACE provides all medical care through their own team of doctors, nurses, and specialists. Your parent will get new primary care providers, but PACE coordinates all their care in one place."
          },
          {
            "question": "What if my parent needs to go to the nursing home later?",
            "answer": "PACE covers nursing facility care when needed. Because they already manage your parent's care, the transition is coordinated by the same team rather than starting over with new providers."
          },
          {
            "question": "How much help does my parent need to qualify for 'nursing facility level of care'?",
            "answer": "Generally, your parent needs daily help with activities like bathing, dressing, medication management, or mobility. Kansas will do a clinical assessment to determine if they meet this level of need."
          },
          {
            "question": "What happens if we move to a county without PACE?",
            "answer": "Your parent would lose PACE coverage if they move outside the service area. They'd need to find new Medicare and Medicaid providers in their new location."
          },
          {
            "question": "Does PACE provide transportation to appointments?",
            "answer": "Yes. PACE includes medical transportation as part of their services, so your parent gets rides to appointments, the day center, and other PACE activities."
          }
        ],
