        "faqs": [
          {
            "question": "Can Mom keep her house if she qualifies for PACE?",
            "answer": "Yes. Your parent's primary home does not count toward the $2,000 asset limit. PACE is specifically designed to help seniors stay in their communities rather than move to nursing facilities."
          },
          {
            "question": "What if her income is just over the $2,901 limit?",
            "answer": "She may still qualify through Medicaid spend-down rules, where excess income can be applied to medical expenses. Contact your local PACE provider to discuss options — Virginia's Medicaid long-term care rules may allow higher income in some situations."
          },
          {
            "question": "Can she still see her current doctors after joining PACE?",
            "answer": "No. PACE becomes the sole provider of all Medicare and Medicaid services. Your parent will need to use PACE's interdisciplinary team of doctors and specialists. However, this team coordinates all care, eliminating the need to manage multiple providers."
          },
          {
            "question": "What happens if PACE isn't available in our area?",
            "answer": "PACE is not statewide in Virginia. If it's not available in your parent's area, look into Virginia's Medicaid waiver programs like the Elderly or Disabled with Consumer Direction (EDCD) waiver, which also helps seniors avoid nursing home placement."
          },
          {
            "question": "How is this different from regular Medicare and Medicaid?",
            "answer": "PACE combines Medicare and Medicaid benefits into one coordinated program with additional services like adult day care and respite care. Instead of managing multiple providers, one interdisciplinary team handles all medical care, therapy, and support services."
          },
          {
            "question": "Can she leave PACE if she doesn't like it?",
            "answer": "Yes. PACE enrollment is voluntary and your parent can disenroll at any time. However, leaving PACE may affect her prior Medicare and Medicaid coverage, so discuss the implications with the PACE team before disenrolling."
          }
        ],
